        <para>An edited volume typically does not have an author, but one or more editors, a title, a place and time of publication and an extent in number of pages or
            volumes.&#160; </para>
        <para>Again, an edited volume does not <i>have</i> to occur inside something else, but it can: it can be part of a series, and here it follows the pattern of
            the monograph. </para>
        <para>If "articles" are publications that occur inside periodicals, let us then say that edited volumes consist of "edited volume
            contributions." An edited volume contribution has one or more authors and a title and then it occurs inside an edited volume: here one usually notes
            the title of the edited volume, its editor(s), its place and time of publication, and finishes off with the location of the contribution inside the
            edited volume. </para>
        <para>We see here the same three-division structure that we noted in relation to the monograph inside a series.</para>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <span class="publication">Carr, Anne, and Douglas J. Schuurman. "Religion and Feminism: A Reformist Christian Analysis."</span> In<span class="container">
                    <em> Religion, Feminism, and the
                Family</em>, edited by Anne Carr and Mary Stewart Van Leeuwen</span>, <span class="location">11-32</span>. <span class="publication">Louisville, KY: Westminster John Knox Press, 1996</span>.</li>
            <li>
                <span class="publication">Demos, John. "Real Lives and Other Fictions: Reconsidering Wallace Stegner's <em>Angle of Repose</em>."</span> In <span class="container">
                    <em>Novel History:
                Historians and Novelists Confront America's Past (and Each Other)</em>, edited by Mark C. Carnes</span>, <span class="location">132-45</span>. <span class="publication">New York: Simon and Schuster,
                2001</span>.</li>
        </ul>
        <para>An edited volume may well be part of a series: a constribution occurs within an antholgy that occurs within a series. On the Container tab for a contribution to an edited volume, one is therefore able to record the title of the series that the edited volume belongs to and its location within the series.</para>
